body: @waelCh when `in_memory` is false, Ludwig saves the preprocessed images to a hdf5 file. The error you are getting suggests me that either the hdf5 already exists or that it cannot be written. Can you verify this please?

You probably have several images of different sizes. if that's the case, inside your image input feature in the definition add:
```
preprocessing:
  width: 100
  height: 100
```
With the values you want, so that Ludwig will resize all images to the same size.
Also, please use the version of Ludwig on master as we solved a few issues about this, v0.1.1 will include them.

@w4nderlust:
- Actually I have already resized all the images to be ```(150,150)```
However I always mention the preprocessing section to avoid any confusion. (Since I get many errors if I don't mention the preprocessing section)

- When I compile and start working with the master version, Ludwig always displays v0.1.0. is that a bug or the system keeps working with the anterior version? 
PS: in the first time, I installed ludwig using ```apt-get```

It's still 0.1.0 yes.
If you resize the images, but the tensors mismatch, the only explanation that I can think of is that the first time you run it you did the preprocessing and saved into hdf5 without resizing. So please delete the hdf5 and json file from the directory where the data lives and start again an experiment.

@Belginwls  please follow the same instructions I already gave in this discussion

WORKING SOLUTION:

1. Go to: Miniconda3\Lib\site-packages or wherever h5py is installed.
2. Delete h5py Folder
3. Delete h5py-2.10.0.dist-info Folder (This might be different if you have a different version).
4. Install h5py again.

It worked for me after a long search. Finally, I tried to delete it manually and reinstall it. IT WORKED!!!!!

By uninstalling them using cmd, pip, anaconda Some files might be stuck and will cause errors even after installing a different version.
